in nmcli i want to show which wifi router of my eero network i'm connected to, and see what the signal strength is as a percentage
To see which specific eero node you are connected to and its signal strength using nmcli, you can use the device wifi command with custom fields. 
Commands to View Connection Details
Show current connection only:
To see just the active access point, its BSSID (MAC address), and signal strength percentage, run:
bash
nmcli -f IN-USE,BSSID,SSID,SIGNAL device wifi | grep '*'
Use code with caution.

Show all nearby nodes (detailed list):
If you want to see all your eero nodes and compare their signal strengths:
bash
nmcli -f IN-USE,BSSID,SSID,SIGNAL,BARS device wifi
Use code with caution.

 
Identifying Your eero Node
Since eero networks typically use the same SSID (network name) for every node, you must look at the BSSID column. 
BSSID: This is the unique MAC address of the specific radio on the eero node you are currently talking to.
SIGNAL: This column displays the signal strength as a percentage (0-100). 
Limitations for 2026
While nmcli provides the hardware address (BSSID), it does not show the "friendly name" you gave the node in the eero app (e.g., "Living Room eero"). To map a BSSID to a specific room, you may need to check the eero App under the "Devices" tab, where you can match the MAC address to the node name. 




