where is it remembering which network to join? where is the list? some connection profile?
In Linux, NetworkManager stores your saved Wi-Fi networks as Connection Profiles. These are simple text files that contain the SSID, security keys, and auto-connect settings.
1. Where the files are stored
On most distributions, these profiles are stored in a protected system directory:
Path: /etc/NetworkManager/system-connections/
Access: You need sudo (root) permissions to view them because they contain your Wi-Fi passwords in plain text or encrypted form.
2. How to list them via command line
You can view the list of saved profiles using nmcli:
bash
nmcli connection show
Use code with caution.

This list includes all saved networks, not just the active one.
3. How to view the details of a specific profile
If you want to see the specific settings for your eero network (such as whether it is set to auto-connect or if it is locked to a specific BSSID), run:
bash
nmcli connection show "Your_SSID_Name"
Use code with caution.

4. How the "Auto-Connect" logic works
NetworkManager uses a specific property to decide whether to join a network automatically. You can check the priority of your networks with this command:
bash
nmcli -f NAME,UUID,AUTOCONNECT,AUTOCONNECT-PRIORITY connection show
Use code with caution.

AUTOCONNECT: If this is yes, the system will attempt to join this network whenever it is in range.
AUTOCONNECT-PRIORITY: If you have multiple saved networks in the same area, NetworkManager will pick the one with the higher number.
5. Managing the List
To prevent a network from auto-connecting:
nmcli connection modify "Your_SSID_Name" connection.autoconnect no
To "forget" (delete) a network:
nmcli connection delete "Your_SSID_Name"
For more detailed technical documentation on how these profiles are structured, you can refer to the NetworkManager Project Documentation.



my network name is "bugger's kingdom". sadly i set it up with an apostrophe. this causes it to have trouble recognizing it. in particular nmcli device wifi connect "bugger's kingom" doesn't work. i've tried all variants with escape sequences, but nothing works. suggestions?
To connect to an SSID containing an apostrophe, you must navigate the "double parsing" of both the Linux shell (Bash/ZSH) and the nmcli internal parser.
Since single quotes ' and double quotes " are often consumed by the shell before nmcli sees them, the most reliable methods in 2026 are:
1. Use the BSSID (Recommended)
The easiest way to bypass naming issues entirely is to connect using the MAC address of the eero node. This avoids all character escaping problems.
Find the BSSID for your network:
nmcli device wifi list | grep "bugger's kingdom"
Connect using that BSSID:
nmcli device wifi connect AA:BB:CC:11:22:33
2. Double-Quote + Backslash Escape
If you want to use the name, you must wrap the entire string in double quotes and use a backslash to escape the apostrophe so the shell doesn't interpret it as the start of a single-quoted string.
bash
nmcli device wifi connect "bugger\'s kingdom"
Use code with caution.

3. Use the Hex-Encoded SSID
If your terminal continues to struggle with the character, you can provide the SSID in hex format. You can find the hex string by running:
bash
nmcli -f SSID-HEX,SSID device wifi list
Use code with caution.

Then connect using the hex string (no quotes needed):
bash
nmcli device wifi connect 6275676765722773206b696e67646f6d
Use code with caution.

4. Interactive Connection
If the command line arguments are failing, use the interactive nmcli prompt. This bypasses shell argument parsing entirely:
Type nmcli to enter the tool.
Type dev wifi connect "bugger's kingdom" inside the prompt.
5. Cleaning up the Saved Profile
If you have an old, broken profile saved, it might be conflicting. Check your existing profiles and delete any that look incorrect:
bash
nmcli connection show
nmcli connection delete "bugger's kingdom"
Use code with caution.

For more troubleshooting on SSID naming conventions, the NetworkManager Manual provides a full list of character escape sequences supported by the utility.



when i use the ssid-hex, it says Parameter <thingigaveit> is neither SSID nor BSSID
In 2026, nmcli handles hex inputs strictly. When you provide the hex-encoded SSID, you must explicitly prefix it with hex: so the parser knows it is not a literal string.
Run the command as follows:
bash
nmcli device wifi connect hex:6275676765722773206b696e67646f6d
Use code with caution.

Why your previous attempt failed:
Ambiguity: Without the hex: prefix, nmcli treats the long string of numbers and letters as a literal SSID name. Since no network is literally named "6275676...", it fails.
The Apostrophe: By using the hex: prefix, you are passing the raw data to the network card, bypassing the shell's confusion over the apostrophe in "bugger's kingdom".
If you still get an error:
Verify the Hex: Ensure you have the exact hex string from your specific environment, as small differences in spacing or hidden characters in the SSID can change the hex. Get it fresh with:
bash
nmcli -f SSID-HEX,SSID device wifi list | grep "bugger"
Use code with caution.

Rescan: Sometimes the BSSID cache is stale. Force a refresh before connecting:
bash
nmcli device wifi rescan
Use code with caution.

For further details on how NetworkManager handles special character encoding, you can consult the NetworkManager.conf documentation.




