same. now it says Parameter 'hex:thingigaveit' is neither SSID nor BSSID
If nmcli is refusing the hex: prefix, it typically means your version of the tool expects the raw hex string directly but is failing because it's interpreting the string as a literal name rather than a hex-encoded SSID.
To solve this for "bugger's kingdom" in 2026, use Method 1, which completely bypasses the SSID name.
Method 1: The "Bulletproof" BSSID Method
The BSSID is the hardware MAC address of the eero node. It has no special characters and never fails due to parsing errors.
Find the BSSID for your network (it will look like AA:BB:CC:11:22:33):
bash
nmcli -f BSSID,SIGNAL,SSID device wifi list | grep "bugger"
Use code with caution.

Connect directly to that BSSID:
bash
nmcli device wifi connect AA:BB:CC:11:22:33
Use code with caution.

Method 2: Manual Profile Creation
If the device wifi connect command keeps failing because of the apostrophe, you can manually create a connection profile. This defines the SSID exactly as it should be in the configuration file. 
Run this command (replace YOUR_PASSWORD with your actual Wi-Fi password): 
bash
nmcli connection add type wifi ifname wlan0 con-name "eero-home" ssid "bugger's kingdom" -- wifi-sec.key-mgmt wpa-psk wifi-sec.psk "YOUR_PASSWORD"
Use code with caution.

Note: We use con-name "eero-home" to give the profile a simple nickname that doesn't have an apostrophe, making it easy to manage later.
Once added, bring it up:
bash
nmcli connection up eero-home
Use code with caution.

Method 3: Use the TUI (Graphical-ish)
If the command line is still fighting you, use the built-in text user interface. It handles special characters and escaping automatically:
Run: nmtui
Select "Activate a connection".
Find bugger's kingdom in the list and press Enter.
Enter your password when prompted. 
Summary for 2026
Avoid using hex if the hex: prefix is being rejected; your specific nmcli build may have different SSID-HEX handling.
BSSID connection is the most reliable way to handle eero mesh nodes specifically, as it also allows you to pick the strongest node manually.
Ensure Client Steering is enabled in your eero app to help your device roam better in the future. 




