problem with the bssid method is that it likely connects to a weaker node than is available.
To solve the "weaker node" problem while still bypassing the apostrophe issue, you should use the BSSID method but target only the strongest node. In a mesh system like eero, each node has its own unique BSSID, even though they share the same SSID name.
1. Identify the Strongest eero Node
Run this command to see all eero nodes, sorted by signal strength (highest at the top):
bash
nmcli -f SIGNAL,BSSID,SSID device wifi list --rescan yes | sort -rn
Use code with caution.

2. Connect to the Top BSSID
Look at the top line where the SSID is bugger's kingdom. Take that specific BSSID (e.g., 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E) and connect:
bash
nmcli device wifi connect 00:1A:2B:3C:4D:5E
Use code with caution.

Because you are using a hardware MAC address (BSSID), nmcli will not look at the SSID name at all, completely avoiding the apostrophe error.
3. Make it Automatic (The "Signal Threshold" Fix)
If your Linux device keeps "sticking" to a weak node as you move around, you can configure the connection profile to be more aggressive. First, find your profile name (usually bugger's kingdom or what you named it in nmtui):
bash
nmcli connection show
Use code with caution.

Then, set a Background Scan Threshold. This tells NetworkManager to look for a better node if the current signal drops below a certain percentage (e.g., 65%):
bash
nmcli connection modify "bugger's kingdom" 802-11-wireless.powersave 2
nmcli connection modify "bugger's kingdom" 802-11-wireless.bgscan-threshold 65
Use code with caution.

4. Use the eero App to Confirm
To verify you are now on the correct node, check the eero App. It will show your device's current connection status and which specific eero it is talking to. If the app shows a "Great" connection but your Linux signal is low, ensure Client Steering is toggled ON in the eero app settings.



